ance, delivering hard to ignore statistical evidence of moral exclusion for young people whose lives have been situated on the intimate fault lines of global conflict, and who carry international crises in their backpacks and in their souls.The volume offers a critical conceptual framework to aid in understanding Muslim American identity formation processes, a framework which can also be applied to other groups of marginalized and immigrant youth. In addition, through their innovative data analytic methods that creatively mix youth drawings, intensive individual interviews, focused group discussions, and culturally sensitive survey items, the authors provide an antidote to "qualitative vs. quantitative" arguments that have unnecessarily captured much time and energy in psychology and other behavioral sciences.Muslim American Youth provides a much-needed road map for those seeking to understand how Muslim youth and other groups of immigrant youth negotiate their identities as Americans.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 4aAmerican. 4aMuslim. 4aWith. 4aanecdotes151often. 4adiscrimination. 4agroups. 4aheartbreaking. 4ahilarious151of. 4aidentities. 4aimmigrant. 4amuch-needed. 4anegotiate. 4aother. 4apersonal. 4aprovides. 4aresistance. 4aroadmap. 4aseeking. 4asometimes. 4astories. 4atheir. 4athis. 4athose. 4aunderstand. 4avolume. 4ayouth. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / Developmental / Adolescent.2bisacsh1 aSirin, Selcuk R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814708859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814708859.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  a